  "prompt": "Should we master one programming language or learn multiple?",
  "response": "There are pros and cons to both approaches:\n\nMastering One Language:\nPros:\n- Deep expertise\n- Better understanding of advanced concepts\n- More likely to become an expert/specialist\n- Can focus on language-specific optimizations\n- Better job opportunities in specialized roles\n\nCons:\n- Limited versatility\n- Risk of becoming obsolete if language declines\n- Harder to adapt to different programming paradigms\n\nLearning Multiple Languages:\nPros:\n- Broader skill set\n- Understanding different programming paradigms\n- More adaptable to various job markets\n- Better problem-solving perspectives\n- Easier to learn new languages quickly\n\nCons:\n- Less depth in each language\n- More initial learning curve\n- Potential confusion between language syntaxes\n\nRecommended Approach:\n1. Master one language deeply first\n2. Learn complementary languages\n3. Focus on programming concepts, not just syntax\n4. Choose languages based on your career goals\n\nGood language combinations:\n- Python (versatile)\n- JavaScript (web)\n- Java/Kotlin (enterprise)\n- C++/Rust (systems programming)\n- Swift/Kotlin (mobile)\n\nUltimately, balance depth with breadth based on your career objectives.",
